    <title>Combined summary - [RFC] Proposal: Base58 encoded HD Wallet root key with optional encryption</title>
    <updated>2023-06-08T14:55:26.480105+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2014-March/004644.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>The given context discusses various proposals and updates related to Bitcoin wallets. Jean-Paul Kogelman proposed a method for encoding and encrypting Bitcoin Hierarchical Deterministic (HD) Wallet root keys, which included two encoding methodologies in three lengths each and unencrypted and encrypted wallet prefixes. The updated spec for key-stretching includes a minimum of 8192 rounds of salted PBKDF2-HMAC-SHA512 to protect passphrases, even if the bulk of the work is outsourced to another device. The proposal also added new KDFs, added an entropy field to the encrypted version, and added plausible deniability.The discussion also includes comparisons between BIP 39 and Kogelman's proposal, including differences such as word lists, length of entropy, genesis date field, password typo detection, and user-selectable KDF. Additionally, there are discussions about using bloom filters for typo checking and plausible deniability, outsourcing the KDF computation to a third party, and compatibility issues that could arise with fancier algorithms.In an email thread discussing key stretching for wallets, William Yager suggests allowing semi-trusted devices to do the heavy lifting, but Pavol Rusnak points out that a compromised computer would remove most of the security offered by key stretching. However, they reach a compromise with the inclusion of PBKDF2-HMAC-SHA512 based KDFs.Jean-Paul Kogelman proposed updates to the Bitcoin Improvement Proposal (BIP) that included removing Scrypt dependency, adding new key derivation functions (KDFs), and plausible deniability. The BIP39 word list was integrated into Bitcoinj, which is likely to become the de facto standard for Android, Trezor web, and several desktop wallets. A conversation was held comparing the proposed specification to BIP 0039, with the former offering more features such as a creation date field and password typo detection.The email thread also discussed the integration of the BIP39 word list into Bitcoinj, timestamping and checksums, entropy length options, user selectable KDF, and cross-wallet compatibility. The discussion also covered the feasibility of using PBKDF2-HMAC-SHA512 as a means of encryption for storage wallets. Jean-Paul expressed concerns about users not being notified of password errors when using a cryptocurrency wallet, while Pavol Rusnak argued that it's not possible to have both plausible deniability and typo checking at the same time. William Yager suggested the use of a bloom filter in a BIP for typo checking and plausible deniability.Jean-Paul Kogelman proposed a method for encoding and encrypting Bitcoin Hierarchical Deterministic (HD) Wallet root keys. The proposal includes two encoding methodologies in three lengths each, along with unencrypted and encrypted wallet prefixes. The clear version of the root key contains verification information for integrity checking, while the encrypted version uses salting and a user-selectable Key Derivation Function (KDF) + parameters to resist brute-force attacks at varying degrees and optionally a second password for plausible deniability. Lastly, an email dated March 12, 2014, discussed the timestamp used in MultiBit HD, which is generated by taking the number of days since midnight of Bitcoin genesis block in UTC with modulo 97 checksum appended. Gary Rowe commented on the BIP39 word list being integrated into Bitcoinj and stated that it will likely become the standard for Android, Trezor web, and several desktop wallets.On December 3, 2014, an email thread was initiated discussing the updates made in the spec after incorporating requested features. The Scrypt dependency that was present in initial drafts was removed, and new key derivation functions (KDFs) were added along with plausible deniability, with a reference implementation made available. The benefits of the new specification over BIP 0038 were highlighted, including multiple key derivation functions, seed lengths, explicit BIP 0032 support, creation date field, and plausible deniability. The conversation then shifted to comparing the proposed specification to BIP 0039, which is for key import/export and does not deal with encryption or wallet creation date. William Yager suggested implementing semi-trusted devices such as desktop PCs for secure wallet management, while Pavol Rusnak pointed out the potential vulnerability of disclosing "preH" to a compromised computer between steps 4 and 5, making later steps less important and compromising the password. Yager expressed concerns about compromising wallet security when doing the key stretching work on more powerful devices. The ease of implementing PBKDF2-HMAC-SHA512 for a group of people, even on devices with limited RAM, was discussed, and it can still run reasonably quickly on slow embedded ARM processors.If users are concerned about the potential vulnerability of exposing the password, step 4 can be revisited and adjusted to make password recovery more expensive. Overall, the email thread provided valuable insights into the development of secure Bitcoin</summary>
